202-04-06-08-12 Fifth Avenue, west side, between 25th and 26th Streets. No. 208 will later be remodelled for the Lincoln Trust Company. On the site of the excavation the 12-story Cross Chambers Building (Mark Cross & Co.) is to be constructed. On the right, Cafe Martin, at 212 on the corner, occupies the building recently vacated by Delmonico's; building will be demolished in 1912. See view of the Broadway side of the block, filed under Broadway, and other views of excavation taken the same day.

April 3, 1902

Irving Underhill, Photographer

Fifth Avenue, west side, between 25th and 26th Streets, excavation after wrecking small house at 210 Fifth Avenue, where 12-story Cross Chambers Building (Mark Cross & Co.) is to be erected. On left, No. 208 will later be remodelled to accommodate the Lincoln Trust Company. On the right, the Cafe Martin occupies the premises recently vacated by Delmonico's, which moved up to 44th Street. This building (No. 212) has the more years to stand.

April 3, 1902

Irving Underhill, Photographer

Fifth Avenue, west side, between 25th and 26th Streets, excavation, where 12-story Cross Chambers Building will be constructed. The view is north into the retaining wall of 212, Cafe Martin, which occupies the premises recently vacated by Delmonico's. April 3, 1902.

Irving Underhill, Photographer

Fifth Avenue, west side, between 25th and 26th Streets, excavation after wrecking small house at 210 Fifth Avenue, where 12-story Cross Chambers Building (Mark Cross & Co.) is to be erected. On left, No. 208 will later be remodelled to accommodate the Lincoln Trust Co. On the right, the Cafe Martin occupies the premises recently vacated by Delmonico's, which moved up to 44th Street. This building (No. 212) has ten more years to stand.

Irving Underhill, Photographer

April 3, 1902

210 Fifth Avenue, west side, between 25th and 26th Streets, showing lot cleared out in preparation for erection of 12-story Cross Chambers Building.
Picture taken from Broadway side, looking south.

April 21, 1902

Irving Underhill, Photographer

210 Fifth Avenue, west side, between 25th and 26th Streets, showing lot cleared out in preparation for erection of 12-story Cross Chambers Building.
Picture taken from Broadway side, looking north.

210 Fifth Avenue, west side, between 25th and 26th Streets, showing lot cleared out in preparation for erection of 12-story Cross Chambers Building.
Picture taken from Broadway side, looking north.

April 21, 1902

Irving Underhill, Photographer.

Fifth Avenue & Broadway, west side, at West 25th Street (extreme right) and southward on the Avenue. The Worth Monument (of 1857) separates Fifth Avenue (the photographers vantage point) from Broadway. Utilizing the 24th to 25th Street frontage of the latter are the two hotels, the Albermarle and the Hoffman House. In the block below is the Fifth Avenue Hotel (demolished 1908).

About 1903

Brown Bros., photographers

Fifth Avenue, west side, north from 25th Street.
1907.
Brown Brothers, Photographer.

Fifth Avenue, north from 25th Street, showing traffic conditions on this main thoroughfare at an early date. Note the spire of the Marble Collegiate Reformed Church at the top center. The intersecting street seen in the foreground is 26th Street with the Brunswick Bldg. (right) occupying the Avenue frontage between that and 27th Street.
This photostat is one of a set filed under various Fifth Avenue locations and Police Activities. Similar material appears on page 229 of the March 11, 1909 issue.

About 1909.

Leslies Weekly
Copyright - Judge Co.

208-210 Fifth Avenue, west side, between 25th and 26t Streets. At the right may be seen the demolition of the Cafe Martin, 212 Fifth Avenue, to make way for a twenty-story office building. This building housed Delmonico's until about 1900, when that establishment moved uptown to Fifth Avenue N.E. corner of 44th Street. June 19, 1912.

Wurts Brothers, Photographers

Celebrations, Parades and Municipal Events: The Victory Arch on Fifth Avenue at 25th Street as viewed southward. Thru the center appears the Fuller (Flatiron) Building. On the right, silhouetted against the Fifth Ave. Building, is the Worth Monument.

The view is northward, showing the Avenue thru the center. Broadway is to the left and Madison Square is on the right.

E. 25th Street, south side, west from the East River, showing a row of taxicabs extending towards First Avenue. The 6 story Municipal Lodging House is seen across the roof of the low center structure and backed up to the rear of the J.J. Little and Ives printing and bookbinding plant.

The Metropolitan Life Insurance Company Building top is barely observable.
